events.event_particulars: The respondent in case DIS-IHK-2025-01180 asserts that the Deutsche Institution für Schiedsgerichtsbarkeit e.V.(DIS) lacks jurisdiction to administer the dispute. The respondent bases this assertion on clause 6.2 of the Engagement Letter dated July 1, 2020. According to the respondent, clause 6.2 stipulates that all disputes arising from the agreement shall be settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce Rules of Arbitration by a single arbitrator. The respondent argues that there is no agreement to submit disputes to DIS, therefore DIS lacks jurisdiction.

Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. ("Respondent") submitted a response to the Request for Arbitration dated 6th May 2025 filed by FAMAS Gmbh. The Respondent raised a jurisdictional objection in its response. The response was submitted on behalf of Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. by its duly authorized Company Secretary, Anu Sharma, who is authorized to represent the company in this matter. The Respondent contends that the Request for Arbitration is inadmissible and requests that DIS decline jurisdiction over the matter.

The Engagement Letter executed between Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. and FAMAS Gmbh contains an arbitration agreement. The agreement stipulates that all disputes arising in connection with the agreement shall be finally settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce. This clause provides the framework for resolving any disagreements that may arise from the engagement between the two parties through arbitration proceedings governed by the specified rules.

The document references a "request for arbitration" between Famas GmbH and Elcomponics Sales. It mentions the absence of consent to DIS arbitration, stating that the respondent has never been asked to consent nor has consented to arbitration under DIS rules. The document also refers to arbitration rules (IHK Munchen) and notes that there is no provision in the Engagement Letter permitting submission of disputes to DIS or adoption of DIS procedural rules. This suggests a dispute regarding the applicable arbitration rules and forum.

The Respondent, Elcomponics Sales Pvt Ltd, contends that the Request for Arbitration is inadmissible because DIS (presumably an arbitration institution) lacks jurisdiction to administer the dispute. The Respondent argues that submitting the dispute to DIS is inconsistent with the parties' agreement and represents an attempt by the Claimant to unilaterally impose a forum not agreed upon in the Engagement Letter. Consequently, the Respondent requests that DIS decline jurisdiction over the matter. The Respondent reserves the right to submit further evidence, arguments, or documentation to support this jurisdictional objection and to engage legal counsel if necessary.

Elcomponics Sales Pvt. Ltd. ('Respondent') submitted a response to the Request for Arbitration filed by F AMAS GmbH on May 6, 2025, under case reference DIS-IHK-2025-01180. In this response, the Respondent raised a jurisdictional objection, asserting that the Deutsche Institution für Schiedsgerichtsbarkeit e.V. (DIS) lacks jurisdiction to administer the dispute. The basis for this objection is found in the Engagement Letter dated July 1, 2020, which explicitly states that all disputes shall be settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce, not DIS. The Respondent contends that there was no agreement to submit disputes to DIS, rendering the Request for Arbitration inadmissible. Furthermore, the Respondent reserves the right to present additional evidence or arguments in support of this objection and to engage legal counsel as necessary.

The parties' Engagement Letter dated 1st July 2020 clause 6.2 expressly provides that 'All disputes arising in connection with this Agreement shall be finally settled under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce Rules of Arbitration (the "Rules") by one arbitrator appointed in accordance with said Rules.' There is no agreement to submit disputes to DIS.

Respondent submits that DIS lacks jurisdiction to administer this dispute, as the parties' Engagement Letter does not permit submission of disputes to DIS or adoption of DIS procedural rules. Respondent has never consented to arbitration under DIS rules, and the Request for Arbitration is therefore inadmissible.

Respondent respectfully requests that DIS decline jurisdiction over this matter, as the dispute should be resolved under the Rules of the Munich Chamber of Commerce as specified in the parties' Engagement Letter. Respondent reserves the right to submit further evidence, arguments, or documentation in support of this jurisdictional objection, and to engage legal counsel if necessary.
